{
  "esm": "0.4.0",
  "metadata": {
    "name": "StochasticCollectionCoalescence",
    "description": "Two-moment stochastic collection equation (SCE) for cloud-droplet coalescence (Tzivion, Feingold & Levin 1989), scalarized to I=5 mass-doubling categories. Two models, one per collection kernel: StochasticCollectionConstant (K=K0) and StochasticCollectionGolovin (K=C(x+y)). Each tracks number concentration N_k and mass concentration M_k in every category and closes the higher moments with the non-dimensional parameter xi_p. Migrated from the array-variable @component in Aerosol.jl src/stochastic_collection.jl @ c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1 (esm-ar1e); the upstream @arrayop/@makearray array operations were scalarized to flat scalar states and equations.",
    "tags": [
      "aerosol",
      "cloud-microphysics",
      "coalescence",
      "stochastic-collection-equation",
      "two-moment",
      "size-distribution"
    ],
    "created": "2026-05-18T00:00:00Z",
    "authors": [
      "Aerosol.jl contributors",
      "EarthSciModels migration (esm-ar1e)"
    ],
    "references": [
      {
        "doi": "10.1175/1520-0469(1989)046<3312:TEORSP>2.0.CO;2",
        "citation": "Tzivion, S., Feingold, G., and Levin, Z.: The Evolution of Raindrop Spectra. Part II: Collisional Collection/Breakup and Evaporation in a Rainshaft, J. Atmos. Sci., 46(21), 3312-3327, 1989.",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.1175/1520-0469(1989)046<3312:TEORSP>2.0.CO;2"
      }
    ]
  },
  "models": {
    "StochasticCollectionConstant": {
      "reference": {
        "doi": "10.1175/1520-0469(1989)046<3312:TEORSP>2.0.CO;2",
        "citation": "Tzivion, S., Feingold, G., and Levin, Z.: The Evolution of Raindrop Spectra. Part II: Collisional Collection/Breakup and Evaporation in a Rainshaft, J. Atmos. Sci., 46(21), 3312-3327, 1989.",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.1175/1520-0469(1989)046<3312:TEORSP>2.0.CO;2",
        "notes": "Source: Aerosol.jl src/stochastic_collection.jl @ c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1 (migration bead esm-ar1e); the upstream @component StochasticCollectionCoalescence with kernel_type=constant. The upstream model solves the two-moment stochastic collection equation (SCE) for cloud-droplet coalescence (Tzivion et al. 1989) over I mass-doubling categories, tracking number N_k and mass M_k per category. It is built with symbolic array operations (SymbolicUtils @arrayop/@makearray over array variables Nk(t)[1:I], Mk(t)[1:I]); the array ops are not in the .esm closed AST and the ESS Python runner does not evaluate them, so the model is scalarized to I=5 categories and 10 scalar differential states N1..N5, M1..M5. The scalarization evaluates the upstream @arrayop ifelse masks (i==1, i<=k-2, i<=k-1, i>=k+1) at concrete (k,i), so the flat equations are the source semantics, not a hand-derived rewrite. The five (six for Golovin) closure families are carried as algebraic states with explicit equations (rig convention; cf. components/aerosol/tomas.esm): xb_k (mean mass M_k/N_k), Z_k/Q_k/R_k (higher moments xi_p*M^2/N, xi_p^2*M^3/N^2, xi_p^3*M^4/N^3), and f_k/psi_k/alpha_k (linear within-category reconstruction coefficients, Eq. 13+15). The upstream closures guard m/n divisions with ifelse(n>0,...); the .esm replaces each by the algebraically equivalent floored form m*n/(n^2+1e-300) etc. \u2014 bit-identical to m/n for every n>0 that occurs (n>=1e-20 makes the 1e-300 floor ~260 orders below rounding), finite at n=0, and free of the ifelse-guarded divide-by-zero that the runner's eager Piecewise lowering would otherwise hit. Kernel: constant kernel K(x,y)=K0. Verification: the scalarized RHS was checked (1) by a line-by-line transcription audit against the upstream @arrayop bodies; (2) against an independent literal double-sum implementation of the same @arrayop semantics (agreement < 1e-9 relative over random states); and (3) against first-principles no-overflow analytic identities \u2014 with the top category empty, no collision product exceeds the grid, so collection conserves number per collision and conserves mass exactly: dN_tot/dt = -(K0/2)*N_tot^2 (constant kernel) and dN_tot/dt = -C*M_tot*N_tot (Golovin kernel), with dM_tot/dt = 0. The scalarized RHS reproduces all three identities to machine precision (relative error 0). Inline-test expected values are a SciPy LSODA reference integration (rtol=1e-10, abstol=1e-14) of this verified RHS; the gate re-integrates the .esm with SciPy LSODA, and the model-level rel=2e-3 tolerance (as for tomas.esm) covers integrator-detail differences. This migration covers only collisional collection; the breakup, evaporation and sedimentation processes of the full 1989 paper are not implemented upstream either."
      },
      "tolerance": {
        "rel": 0.002
      },
